          "thumbURL": "assets/data/cn/02_ManchurianTiger/protection/thumb/1.jpg",
          "text": "The largest breeding base of the Red Crowned Crane in China - Zhalong National Nature Reserve, Heilongjiang Province."
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p>The number of Siberian tigers once dropped sharply. Protection of the animal and its natural ecological environment has been included in China’s national development strategy. With upgraded protection, the population is steadily rising.</p><p>On May 29, 1993, the Chinese government promulgated the <i>Notice Concerning the Ban of the Trade of Rhinoceros Horns and Tiger Bones</i>, prohibiting the import and export, as well as the sale, acquisition, transportation, carrying and mailing of tiger bones, canceling the standards for use of tiger bones for medicinal purposes and forbidding any pharmacy to hold tiger bones in any form. China used to be the country with the largest demand for tiger products in the world. The ban promulgated by the Chinese government curbed market demand and effectively prevented the extinction of wild tigers.</p><p>Jilin Hunchun Manchurian Tiger Nature Reserve was established in December 2001 and successfully upgraded to a national nature reserve three years later. </p><p>In 2017, the Chinese government established the National Park for Manchurian Tiger and Amur Leopard in the vast border areas of Jilin and Heilongjiang provinces, covering an area of 14,600 square kilometers. It is much larger than the original tiger and leopard reserve in China. According to the <i>Plan of Jilin Province on Major Ecological Protection Project of Wild Manchurian Tigers and Amur Leopards</i>, by 2025, the Chinese government will form a tiger and leopard distribution area of over 20,000 square kilometers in Changbai Mountains.</p>"
